WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.370 --> 00:00:06.430
Katina: Thank you all for coming to this "Authors
at Google" Talk. My name is Katina Johnson,

00:00:06.430 --> 00:00:10.769
and I'm a Manager in Online Sales and Operations.
I'm please to introduce our guest speaker

00:00:10.769 --> 00:00:15.960
today, Amy Goodman. Goodman is an award winning
journalist, investigative journalist and syndicated

00:00:15.960 --> 00:00:21.529
columnist. Um...she’s an author and host
of Democracy Now which airs on more than 800

00:00:21.529 --> 00:00:26.970
public TV and radio stations worldwide. She's
had four New York Times best sellers, three

00:00:26.970 --> 00:00:31.669
of those were co-authored with her brother,
uh, journalist David Goodman. And, in fact,

00:00:31.669 --> 00:00:37.579
when Amy was here last, it was in April of
2008. She and her brother promoted their book,

00:00:37.579 --> 00:00:42.440
"Standing Up To the Madness." That was also
a time when the presidential, uh, campaign

00:00:42.440 --> 00:00:47.390
was starting to heat up, and with all that's
happened in politics in the last couple of

00:00:47.390 --> 00:00:51.899
years since then, it seems as like there's
even more madness to, to stand up to now.

00:00:51.899 --> 00:00:56.900
Um, and that's exactly what her role has been
during her career as a journalist. So today

00:00:56.900 --> 00:01:01.359
she's going to talk about her most recent
book, "Breaking the Sound Barrier". It's a

00:01:01.359 --> 00:01:06.220
collection of wide-ranging articles that cover
a lot of the hot button issues, uh, like the

00:01:06.220 --> 00:01:12.280
wars and one that definitely front-of-mind
in the news, immigration. Bill Moyers, who

00:01:12.280 --> 00:01:16.530
wrote the introduction, describes it as a
reality check. He goes on to say that you

00:01:16.530 --> 00:01:21.720
can learn more of the truth about Washington
and the world from one week of Amy Goodman's

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:26.080
"Democracy Now" than from a year of Sunday
morning talk shows. So, we only have an hour

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:30.020
today. She's going to talk for about 45 minutes,
uh, but I suspect that there's a lot that

00:01:30.020 --> 00:01:36.250
we can learn from her right now. So please
join me in welcoming Amy Goodman.

00:01:36.250 --> 00:01:47.660
Amy Goodman:
Well, it's great to be here and hello to everyone

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:55.220
in the satellite facilities. Um, well, I,
why don't I start off by asking how many of

00:01:55.220 --> 00:02:01.410
you have ever seen, or heard, or read "Democracy
Now" online? Where do you watch it? Online?

00:02:01.410 --> 00:02:02.610
Male audience member:
Online?

00:02:02.610 --> 00:02:03.610
Amy Goodman:
Uh, radio?

00:02:03.610 --> 00:02:05.020
Male audience member:
KPFA?

00:02:05.020 --> 00:02:10.060
Amy Goodman:
KPFA? Television? KRSB, CBS, and Public Access

00:02:10.060 --> 00:02:16.030
in Marin County, and depending on where you
are. Uh, well, I originally come from Pacifica

00:02:16.030 --> 00:02:23.140
Radio which was founded 61 years ago um...
in the Bay Area, uh, in Berkeley, KPFA the

00:02:23.140 --> 00:02:28.750
first station. And it was founded by a man
named Lou Hill. He was a WWII conscientious

00:02:28.750 --> 00:02:33.849
objector. Uh, When he came out the detention
camps, he said that there has got to be a

00:02:33.849 --> 00:02:40.200
media outlet that is run not by corporations
that profit from war, but run by journalists

00:02:40.200 --> 00:02:49.560
and artists, and that's how Pacifica was formed.
Um, the first Pacifica station, KPFA '49 and

00:02:49.560 --> 00:03:00.639
KCFK in Los Angeles '59, 1960 my station in
New York, WBAI, WPFW in Washington 1977, KPFT

00:03:00.639 --> 00:03:06.580
in Houston 1970. Those are the five Pacifica
stations. That station in Houston is the only

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:12.010
one in the country who transmitter was blown
up. Uh, in the first few months of operation

00:03:12.010 --> 00:03:17.340
the Ku Klux Klan strapped dynamite to the
base of the transmitter and blew it to smithereens.

00:03:17.340 --> 00:03:21.909
And when they got back on their feet, they
blew it up again. Now the silver lining was

00:03:21.909 --> 00:03:25.590
it's not as if they had money for advertising
or anything, so it certainly blew it into

00:03:25.590 --> 00:03:30.189
the conscientiousness of the potential listening
audience of the people of Houston. I don't

00:03:30.189 --> 00:03:35.390
remember if it was the Grand Dragon or the
Exalted Cyclops because I often confuse their

00:03:35.390 --> 00:03:42.400
titles, but he said it was his proudest act.
And I think that's because he understood how

00:03:42.400 --> 00:03:48.629
dangerous Pacifica is, how dangerous independent
media is because it allows people to speak

00:03:48.629 --> 00:03:55.230
for themselves. And when you hear someone
speaking from their own experience whether

00:03:55.230 --> 00:04:02.430
a Palestinian child, an Israeli grandmother,
an Afghan aunt, an uncle from Afghanistan.

00:04:02.430 --> 00:04:07.889
You come to understand them a little better.
You don't necessarily have to agree, but you

00:04:07.889 --> 00:04:13.489
understand where they're coming from. We need
a media in this country that builds bridges

00:04:13.489 --> 00:04:19.840
between communities rather than advocates
the bombing of bridges. The media can be a

00:04:19.840 --> 00:04:26.639
great force for peace. But that's not how
it's used in this country. I just came from

00:04:26.639 --> 00:04:35.699
uh Stanford, speaking last night, to a conference
today on the future of journalism. And for

00:04:35.699 --> 00:04:45.500
all of the new wave interesting ways of distributing
media and all the new possibilities and what

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:51.080
with newspapers folding, what does it mean,
and where is journalism going, I think we

00:04:51.080 --> 00:04:57.199
still have to get back to the very important
basics of journalism, holding those in power

00:04:57.199 --> 00:05:01.099
accountable, simple as that. Uh, my brother,
David, and I wrote these three books: the

00:05:01.099 --> 00:05:04.690
first is called the "Exception to the Rulers",
and that's what media should be; that's the

00:05:04.690 --> 00:05:10.569
motto of democracy now, The Exception to the
Rulers. The second one is called "Static",

00:05:10.569 --> 00:05:15.289
and the reason we call it that is because
in this high tech digital age with high definition

00:05:15.289 --> 00:05:21.889
television and digital radio still all we
ever get is static. That veil of distortion,

00:05:21.889 --> 00:05:27.240
lies, misrepresentations, and half truths
that obscure reality when what we need is

00:05:27.240 --> 00:05:33.300
the dictionary definition of static, criticism,
opposition, unwanted interference. We need

00:05:33.300 --> 00:05:38.379
a media that covers power, not covers for
power. We need a media that is the fourth

00:05:38.379 --> 00:05:46.479
estate, not for the state. And we need a media
that covers the movement that creates static

00:05:46.479 --> 00:05:47.479
and make history.

00:05:47.479 --> 00:05:51.729
Um, and that's not the kind of media we have
in this country. People talk a lot about how

00:05:51.729 --> 00:05:57.789
the reason newspapers are being shuttered
around the country is, well because of the

00:05:57.789 --> 00:06:03.220
internet. There's other ways to get information.
I think that's partly true. But I also think

00:06:03.220 --> 00:06:14.050
newspapers buried themselves by not telling
the truth, by icing out the voices of dissent

00:06:14.050 --> 00:06:19.580
that really are what could have saved them
and all of us. I mean, let's just look at

00:06:19.580 --> 00:06:25.930
the lead up to the invasion of Iraq. And the
reason I go back to this, it is so important.

00:06:25.930 --> 00:06:35.020
A country can't make a more serious decision
than going to war, than sending young men

00:06:35.020 --> 00:06:39.490
and women and not-so-young men and women to
kill or be killed. And so we should talk about

00:06:39.490 --> 00:06:45.810
it all the time when we're doing it, and we
are doing it big time. In Iraq we just passed

00:06:45.810 --> 00:06:52.539
the seventh anniversary of the war. In Afghanistan,
we're on nine years, longer than the U.S.

00:06:52.539 --> 00:07:00.889
was involved in Vietnam. It's truly astounding.
Um, about five weeks before the U.S. invaded

00:07:00.889 --> 00:07:07.419
Iraq, uh, General Collin Powell, then Secretary
of State, gave his push for war at the United

00:07:07.419 --> 00:07:14.240
Nations. Um, the group FAIR, Fairness And
Accuracy In Reporting, did this study of the

00:07:14.240 --> 00:07:21.060
two weeks around that speech that was February
5th, 2003. They looked at the four major nightly

00:07:21.060 --> 00:07:26.469
news casts, NBC Nightly News, CBS Evening
News, ABC World News Tonight, and uh, PBS

00:07:26.469 --> 00:07:34.370
News Hour with Jim Lehrer. Four news casts,
the agenda-setting news in this country. In

00:07:34.370 --> 00:07:41.300
that two week period, there were 393 interviews
done around war. Guess how many were with

00:07:41.300 --> 00:07:46.680
anti-war leaders? Silence. [Audience guessing.]
Underestimate 0.

00:07:46.680 --> 00:07:50.310
(audience murmuring)
But you're close.

00:07:50.310 --> 00:07:52.949
(audience murmuring)
Still an underestimate, 1.

00:07:52.949 --> 00:07:59.960
(More audience murmuring)
Uh, you overestimated, 5. So, 3. Three of

00:07:59.960 --> 00:08:07.629
almost 400 were with anti-war leaders. That
is no longer a mainstream media 'cause about

00:08:07.629 --> 00:08:13.690
half the population was opposed to war then.
But they brought out 3 of 400 voices? That's

00:08:13.690 --> 00:08:18.960
an extreme media beating the drums for war.
And I really do believe that those who were

00:08:18.960 --> 00:08:24.650
opposed to war, those who were opposed to
torture are not a fringe minority. Not even

00:08:24.650 --> 00:08:31.300
a silent majority, but the "silenced" majority;
silenced by the corporate media which is why

00:08:31.300 --> 00:08:39.479
we have to take it back. It really does matter.
I think the media are the most powerful institutions

00:08:39.479 --> 00:08:45.362
on earth. More powerful than any bomb, more
powerful than any missile, and the Pentagons

00:08:45.362 --> 00:08:51.890
deploy the media, so we've got to get it back.
I think the embedding process brought the

00:08:51.890 --> 00:08:57.490
media to an all-time low. You know, the embedding
process where reporters get embedded, and

00:08:57.490 --> 00:09:03.190
the front lines of troops which Victoria Clark,
who was spokesperson for the Pentagon, helped

00:09:03.190 --> 00:09:09.480
craft the whole "embed" program, called it
a spectacular success which, of course, why

00:09:09.480 --> 00:09:17.760
it's a very serious failure. Um, the idea
of the embedding process is you get this,

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:23.600
you know, immediate view, yes, but from only
one perspective - from the trigger end of

00:09:23.600 --> 00:09:28.940
the war. I'm not say reporters aren't brave
who are embedded, but when you're sleeping

00:09:28.940 --> 00:09:34.000
with the troops, eating with the troops, when
your life is in their hands, you are going

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:41.279
to report a certain way. And you have a certain
perspective. If you're going to have reporters

00:09:41.279 --> 00:09:46.230
embedded in troops, you need reporters embedded
in Afghan hospitals, in Iraqi communities,

00:09:46.230 --> 00:09:51.750
in the peace movement around the world to
understand the full effects of war. And the

00:09:51.750 --> 00:09:58.290
problem isn't only the embedding process in
troops, uh, covering troops; it's being embedded

00:09:58.290 --> 00:10:05.520
in the establishment in Washington. You know
how often you hear these softball questions

00:10:05.520 --> 00:10:12.130
at the White House; we call it the access
of evil. Right? Trading truth for access,

00:10:12.130 --> 00:10:18.790
and it not worth it. It's a disservice.

00:10:18.790 --> 00:10:24.880
We have to protect journalism, and we have
to promote journalism. Reporters around the

00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:32.360
world face very serious consequences for their
work, especially Arab media workers and journalists

00:10:32.360 --> 00:10:36.550
in Iraq and Afghanistan. I want to talk about
Wikileaks in a minute.

00:10:36.550 --> 00:10:41.390
Um, but I want to talk about something less
serious, but it does have serious ramifications.

00:10:41.390 --> 00:10:47.440
And that was the recent trip that I took with
my colleagues just from here to Vancouver,

00:10:47.440 --> 00:10:55.190
or attempted to take. It was Thanksgiving,
and um, uh, I was on a book tour for "Breaking

00:10:55.190 --> 00:10:59.850
the Sound Barrier". And since everyone was
eating turkey here, we thought we'd talk turkey

00:10:59.850 --> 00:11:06.540
in Canada. So we headed from Seattle to the
border and then up to Vancouver. I was going

00:11:06.540 --> 00:11:10.310
to be speaking from the Vancouver Public Library.
Wherever we go, we hold fundraisers for the

00:11:10.310 --> 00:11:16.579
community stations that run "Democracy Now",
and there are three radio stations in Vancouver.

00:11:16.579 --> 00:11:23.209
So we're crossing the border, it's Wednesday
of Thanksgiving, and we hand them our passports,

00:11:23.209 --> 00:11:28.300
and they pull us over. They flag us. And they
tell us that we've got to go into this big

00:11:28.300 --> 00:11:33.620
border facility. So we go in. It's pouring
rain, and it's really close to the talk. So

00:11:33.620 --> 00:11:37.899
I have to get out of there so that I can go
up to the library. And, uh, you know, they

00:11:37.899 --> 00:11:43.320
call me up, uh, to the counter. They say,
uh, "Amy, we want your notes." I said, "My

00:11:43.320 --> 00:11:50.160
notes for what?" They said, "Your notes for
your talk tonight." Well, now, I don't really

00:11:50.160 --> 00:11:56.481
speak from notes, so I went out to the car,
and I got a copy of the book. And I came in,

00:11:56.481 --> 00:12:00.700
and I gave it to them. And there were three
guards. You know they were all armed. One

00:12:00.700 --> 00:12:05.880
of them was entering everything I was saying
into a computer. Another was handwriting down

00:12:05.880 --> 00:12:10.089
everything I was saying, and the other started
reading the book which I took as a good sign.

00:12:10.089 --> 00:12:11.089
(laughter)

00:12:11.089 --> 00:12:16.509
So they said, "What are you going to be talking
about tonight?" And I was very taken aback,

00:12:16.509 --> 00:12:21.111
and, but it sort of a no-man's land there.
You don't know what your rights are, and I

00:12:21.111 --> 00:12:27.050
really had to get there. So I said, "Well,
I was going to start with the last column.

00:12:27.050 --> 00:12:32.089
What I basically do is I, uh, read excerpts
of columns", I said, "and I riff off them."

00:12:32.089 --> 00:12:43.029
So I was going to start with the last column,
um, which is about Tommy Douglas, title "Healthcare

00:12:43.029 --> 00:12:48.690
Reform Needs an Action Hero". Tommy Douglas,
who is considered the greatest Canadian. He

00:12:48.690 --> 00:12:52.760
was the Premier of Saskatchewan in the early
60's. Well, when he was a kid he almost lost

00:12:52.760 --> 00:12:58.080
his leg, and a doctor offered to, uh, help
him for free. He was poor, and so when he

00:12:58.080 --> 00:13:01.880
grew up and he became a politician, he thought,
"The one thing I want to bring to Canada is

00:13:01.880 --> 00:13:06.529
single-payer healthcare, is national healthcare
system." It's what they call Medicare. And

00:13:06.529 --> 00:13:13.019
so, as Premier of Sasketchewan he introduced
it. And his major opponent was the American

00:13:13.019 --> 00:13:18.449
Medical Association, right? Based here. Why?
Because they were afraid the contagion would

00:13:18.449 --> 00:13:25.459
spread south. And they led a, like three-week
strike of Canadian doctors, but Tommy Douglas

00:13:25.459 --> 00:13:31.600
won. And they adopted Medicare in Saskatchewan.
Then he traversed Canada until it was adopted

00:13:31.600 --> 00:13:39.149
everywhere. Extremely popular program in Canada.
Um, I'm telling the guards this story, the

00:13:39.149 --> 00:13:42.680
Canadian guards. This is the Canadian side
of the border. I said, "I don't really get

00:13:42.680 --> 00:13:47.490
it. I'm being detained here. Sara Palin just
came here and trashed your system! She was

00:13:47.490 --> 00:13:52.649
able to go all over Canada!" Anyway, so I
said, "So, I wrote my column on it because..."

00:13:52.649 --> 00:13:59.210
Well, this is how I started it. "Imagine the
scene, America 2009. 18,000 people have died

00:13:59.210 --> 00:14:04.060
in one year, an average of almost 50 a day.
Who's taking them out, or, what's killing

00:14:04.060 --> 00:14:08.790
them? To investigate, President Obama might
be tempted to call on Jack Bauer, the fictional

00:14:08.790 --> 00:14:14.310
rogue intelligence agent from the hit TV series,
"24", who invariably employs torture and a

00:14:14.310 --> 00:14:18.639
host of other illegal tactics to help the
President fight terrorism. But terrorism isn't

00:14:18.639 --> 00:14:23.970
the culprit here. It's lack of adequate healthcare.
So maybe the President's solution isn't Jack

00:14:23.970 --> 00:14:32.360
Bauer, but rather the actor who plays him".
You know who the star of "24" is? Kiefer Sutherland.

00:14:32.360 --> 00:14:38.250
Well his family has very deep connections
to healthcare reform. His grandfather is Tommy

00:14:38.250 --> 00:14:43.791
Douglas, the man who brought single-payer
healthcare to Canada. Um, "Yes, Kiefer Sutherland

00:14:43.791 --> 00:14:49.560
is the grandson of Tommy Douglas. Um, his
mother is Shirley Douglas, his father is Donald

00:14:49.560 --> 00:14:56.020
Sutherland. And Kiefer Sutherland, if he spoke
out here, would have a tremendous impact.

00:14:56.020 --> 00:15:01.560
You know, he speaks to a very right-wing audience.
He, uh, "24" is like Rush Limbaugh's favorite

00:15:01.560 --> 00:15:08.110
show. Glenn Beck loves it. Rush Limbaugh visited
the set of 24. Um, "he should learn from the

00:15:08.110 --> 00:15:12.709
real life actor who plays his hero, Jack.
Limbaugh and his cohorts might find truth

00:15:12.709 --> 00:15:17.600
not as satisfying as fiction". Now Kiefer
Sutherland does speak out in Canada. He was

00:15:17.600 --> 00:15:22.529
speaking at a big rally in Alberta. He said,
"Private healthcare doesn't work. America's

00:15:22.529 --> 00:15:27.940
trying to change their system. It's too expensive
to get comprehensive medical care in the U.S.

00:15:27.940 --> 00:15:32.070
Why on earth are we going to follow their
system here?" Kiefer Sutherland said, "I consider

00:15:32.070 --> 00:15:36.769
it a humanitarian issue. This is an issue
about what is right and wrong, what is decent

00:15:36.769 --> 00:15:44.750
and what is not". "Maybe Jack Bauer can save
the day," I said to the Canadian border guards.

00:15:44.750 --> 00:15:45.750
(laughter)

00:15:45.750 --> 00:15:50.560
It's getting really late, and they said, "What
else are you talking about?" "So I said, Well,

00:15:50.560 --> 00:15:54.860
I thought I would talk about the global economic
meltdown." "What else are you talking about?"

00:15:54.860 --> 00:15:59.319
they said. I said, "Well, uh, I was going
to talk about global warming." "What else

00:15:59.319 --> 00:16:03.290
are you talking about?" I said, "Well, maybe
this would be the trigger. I was going to

00:16:03.290 --> 00:16:07.730
talk about the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan."
"WHAT ELSE are you talking about?" I said,

00:16:07.730 --> 00:16:10.920
"Well, I only have an hour. That pretty much
does it.”

00:16:10.920 --> 00:16:11.920
(laughter)

00:16:11.920 --> 00:16:13.870
"And they said, "Are you denying you are talking
about the Olympics?"

00:16:13.870 --> 00:16:14.870
(laughter)

00:16:14.870 --> 00:16:15.870
I said, "The Olympics?"

00:16:15.870 --> 00:16:16.870
(laughter)

00:16:16.870 --> 00:16:21.870
I mean anyone who knows me, I'm not really
into watching organized sports, though I do

00:16:21.870 --> 00:16:28.690
like to play sports. And I didn't even know
what they were talking about. This is how

00:16:28.690 --> 00:16:35.850
limited my world it. Um, I said, "Do you mean
when President Obama to Copenhagen to try

00:16:35.850 --> 00:16:39.600
to get the Olympics to Chicago?" And he said,
"Yeah, and you didn't get them." I said, "I

00:16:39.600 --> 00:16:43.800
know we didn't get them. I said, "You mean
the "real Olympics?" He said, "I'm talking

00:16:43.800 --> 00:16:47.079
about the Vancouver Olympics." I said, "Oh."

00:16:47.079 --> 00:16:54.579
I mean it really wasn't on my radar at all.
And I said, "No, well until now I wasn't planning

00:16:54.579 --> 00:17:01.569
to talk about the Olympics." And because I
was so incredulous, he clearly didn't believe

00:17:01.569 --> 00:17:06.390
me. He told me to sit down, and they went
through our car. Um, I was with two colleagues;

00:17:06.390 --> 00:17:10.699
one of them is Chuck Scurich. He's handing
Daily Digest if you want to sign up for our

00:17:10.699 --> 00:17:14.720
daily headlines and news alerts. And folks,
in other places, you can just go to our website

00:17:14.720 --> 00:17:21.539
and sign up. But I was there with Chuck and
Dennis Moynihan, who edited the columns. And,

00:17:21.539 --> 00:17:27.110
uh, they went through everything. They went
through our computers. They were on our computers

00:17:27.110 --> 00:17:31.409
when I went out to check on them, going through
all my notes. It was a very serious violation.

00:17:31.409 --> 00:17:34.299
And when they came in, they brought me in
a back room. They took four pictures of me

00:17:34.299 --> 00:17:39.140
and my colleagues." They stapled what they
called "control documents" into our passports.

00:17:39.140 --> 00:17:43.320
I said, "I didn't think we needed visas to
come into Canada." And they said, "These aren't

00:17:43.320 --> 00:17:47.340
visas; they're control documents". And they
said we had to leave within 48 hours. And

00:17:47.340 --> 00:17:52.539
if you think I talk fast? You should see how
fast I talked for the next 48 hours to get

00:17:52.539 --> 00:17:55.630
everything in. And then we left. And when
I would tell people they would say, "This

00:17:55.630 --> 00:18:02.160
is Canada?" But we learned so much, uh, as
a result. Yes, we made it to Vancouver. Thank

00:18:02.160 --> 00:18:06.140
goodness for Canadians; they'd all gone out
for beer. And they all came back and brought

00:18:06.140 --> 00:18:09.840
their friends. So it was a packed audience.
And it became the top story in Canada. You

00:18:09.840 --> 00:18:13.919
know, American journalist detained at the
border. And CBC and the Toronto Globe and

00:18:13.919 --> 00:18:17.840
Mail and the Toronto Sun. I mean, everywhere
I was going, I was being interviewed. But

00:18:17.840 --> 00:18:22.700
when I watched their pieces, the piece right
after the one covering me, for example, is

00:18:22.700 --> 00:18:26.810
about the Vancouver City Council and how it
had passed legislation that if you had a sign

00:18:26.810 --> 00:18:32.030
in your house that said anything against the
Olympics, your house could be raided. Oh,

00:18:32.030 --> 00:18:36.010
athletes weren't allowed to speak out against
corporations that sponsored the Olympics.

00:18:36.010 --> 00:18:40.940
It was very serious! The issue of free speech
was serious! And you know, two nights ago

00:18:40.940 --> 00:18:45.860
I was speaking at University of Wisconsin
Eau Claire, and, um, (clears throat) that

00:18:45.860 --> 00:18:54.040
afternoon, they, uh, the students invited
people for a free lunch if they were willing

00:18:54.040 --> 00:18:59.059
to give up free speech which is very cool.
It was the journalists' organization there.

00:18:59.059 --> 00:19:03.631
They said anyone who wants, who is willing
to give up free speech and freedom of the

00:19:03.631 --> 00:19:08.169
press, come on in and have lunch. And then
they had protests outside, and you know they

00:19:08.169 --> 00:19:11.429
sort of played this all out. But, you know,
freedom of the press, freedom of speech is

00:19:11.429 --> 00:19:16.580
extremely important. And it was violated there,
especially as they went through our notes.

00:19:16.580 --> 00:19:22.799
Then, um, we've got to take these things seriously.
Like what happened at the Republican Convention

00:19:22.799 --> 00:19:28.559
just two years ago. Uh, let's see. I was here
two years ago. It was a couple months before

00:19:28.559 --> 00:19:34.520
the Convention, and of course, "Democracy
Now" was out in force, "Breaking With Convention",

00:19:34.520 --> 00:19:39.059
"War, Peace and The Presidency, from the streets
to the suites to the convention floor." We

00:19:39.059 --> 00:19:45.250
went to Denver; then we flew on to Minneapolis,
St. Paul to cover the Republican Convention

00:19:45.250 --> 00:19:51.580
after the Democrats. It was the first day
of the Convention, Labor Day. Um, for the

00:19:51.580 --> 00:19:57.650
Republican Convention there was a major protest
that morning of 10,000 people led by soldiers.

00:19:57.650 --> 00:20:02.100
Amazing! Some in full military regalia who
were saying no to war. You know, they take

00:20:02.100 --> 00:20:07.890
great risk in doing this. There is a real
untold story of thousands of soldiers who've

00:20:07.890 --> 00:20:11.691
said no to war, by the way, who've refused
to go. They are according to the Pentagon

00:20:11.691 --> 00:20:15.510
numbers, but they don't like to talk about
it. And then there are those who go to fight

00:20:15.510 --> 00:20:21.860
in Iraq, who go to fight in Afghanistan, or
go again, and again, and again, and again,

00:20:21.860 --> 00:20:25.529
and then they refuse or they just come home
to talk about it. And they were the ones who

00:20:25.529 --> 00:20:30.621
were leading this protest of 10,000. And we
were out covering it, of course. And my colleagues

00:20:30.621 --> 00:20:35.200
went back to SPNN which is St. Paul Neighborhood
Network, the public access station we were

00:20:35.200 --> 00:20:40.559
broadcasting from, and I went off to the Convention
floor to start to cover the Convention. I

00:20:40.559 --> 00:20:47.260
was interviewing delegates from the hottest
state, from Alaska. And, um, and then I got

00:20:47.260 --> 00:20:51.630
a call on our cell phone from, um, from our
senior producer, Mike Burke. He said, "Come

00:20:51.630 --> 00:20:57.251
quickly to 7th and Jackson. Two of our producers,
Nicole and Shariff, were arrested." He said,

00:20:57.251 --> 00:21:01.429
"They were hurt. You've got to get over there."
Uh, that's Nicole, uh, the producer, senior

00:21:01.429 --> 00:21:06.950
producer, and Nicole Salazar, our multi-media
producer. So I raced off the Convention floor,

00:21:06.950 --> 00:21:12.150
and I had all the credentials on that allow
me to interview presidents and vice presidents

00:21:12.150 --> 00:21:16.980
delegates, and I was with our cameraman, Rick
Rowley of Big Noise Films. We raced down the

00:21:16.980 --> 00:21:22.740
street to St. Paul, got to 7th and Jackson,
a big parking lot, and the riot police had

00:21:22.740 --> 00:21:27.679
surrounded the area. They had it totally contained.
I raced up to them. I was out of breath. I

00:21:27.679 --> 00:21:30.590
went up quick. I said, "You can see I have
just come from the Convention floor. I'd like

00:21:30.590 --> 00:21:34.490
to speak to your commanding officer. Uh, you
can see I am a credentialed reporter. We have

00:21:34.490 --> 00:21:38.650
two reporters inside, also fully credentialed.
We need to have them released immediately."

00:21:38.650 --> 00:21:43.180
I mean it wasn't seconds before they ripped
me through that line, twisted my arms back,

00:21:43.180 --> 00:21:47.320
slapped handcuffs on me, pushed me up against
the wall and onto the ground, and arrested

00:21:47.320 --> 00:21:53.140
me. Charged me with a misdemeanor, interfering
with a peace officer. Uh, if only there was

00:21:53.140 --> 00:21:58.280
a peace officer in the vicinity. So I was
on the ground, looking desperately for Nicole

00:21:58.280 --> 00:22:02.169
and Shariff. I see Shariff across the parking
lot, arms behind him back, his back, his arm

00:22:02.169 --> 00:22:06.060
is bleeding. I demand to be brought to him.
Finally they bring me to him, and I was...

00:22:06.060 --> 00:22:10.610
they had really, um, set the handcuffs, made
the handcuffs very tight. I was asking them

00:22:10.610 --> 00:22:15.740
to loosen my handcuffs, so they tightened
them. So we're standing together, Shariiff

00:22:15.740 --> 00:22:20.590
and I. We both have our credentials on. And
we're demanding to be released whereupon the

00:22:20.590 --> 00:22:25.970
Secret Service came and ripped the credentials
from around our necks. Um, then police, uh,

00:22:25.970 --> 00:22:33.370
pulled me over to the police wagon. Um, and
inside there was Nicole. So we're both in

00:22:33.370 --> 00:22:38.289
the police wagon, and Nicole described quickly
to me what had happened. Her face was bleeding,

00:22:38.289 --> 00:22:43.460
she was handcuffed, and she had her press
credential on. Um, she said they were at St.

00:22:43.460 --> 00:22:48.909
Paul Neighborhood Network, digitizing tape,
and, um, they heard a commotion outside. And

00:22:48.909 --> 00:22:53.090
so they dec... they raced down with camera
and microphone. Like if they hadn't, they

00:22:53.090 --> 00:22:58.340
wouldn't have been their job. And they raced
out. They saw protesters. They saw police.

00:22:58.340 --> 00:23:03.120
She started filming, Shariff had the microphone,
and then the riot police came at them. Um,

00:23:03.120 --> 00:23:09.070
en masse, and they're shouting at Nicole and
Shariff, "On your face, on your face." Nicole

00:23:09.070 --> 00:23:13.390
is filming, she is holding her press pass
up, she shouting back, "Press, Press." And

00:23:13.390 --> 00:23:18.980
they take her down on her face. Her camera
tumbles down. The first thing they do is they

00:23:18.980 --> 00:23:23.559
pull the battery out of her camera. If you
were wondering what is was they wanted to

00:23:23.559 --> 00:23:29.320
stop happening. Um, she's on her face. They
have their, her, their knee or boot in her

00:23:29.320 --> 00:23:32.720
back, and they're dragging on her legs. So
it's dragging her face in the dirt which is

00:23:32.720 --> 00:23:37.529
how it got bloodied. And then Shariiff, very
cool guy, he's telling the police to calm

00:23:37.529 --> 00:23:41.659
down. They take him, throw him up against
the wall, kick him twice in the chest, and

00:23:41.659 --> 00:23:47.279
take him down. That's how they bloodied his
arms. So they bring me to the police garage

00:23:47.279 --> 00:23:53.559
where they've erected cages for the protesters.
They bring Nicole and Shariff to jail. Um,

00:23:53.559 --> 00:23:59.500
I faced, I was charged with a misdemeanor;
they faced felony riot charges. Now, if it

00:23:59.500 --> 00:24:04.860
weren't for You Tube, if it weren't for all,
oh, all different means of media getting out,

00:24:04.860 --> 00:24:09.029
I don't know when we would have gotten out.
But within a few hours, I think the video

00:24:09.029 --> 00:24:13.790
of our arrest went up on You Tube within a
half an hour. And the response, apparently,

00:24:13.790 --> 00:24:20.660
was just enormous. Uh, the old fashioned way,
faxing, calling, emailing, people were tweeting

00:24:20.660 --> 00:24:25.870
in, but there was huge demand for our release.
In a few hours I was released and then Shariff

00:24:25.870 --> 00:24:31.049
and Nicole. In fact, Shariff was in jail with,
uh, in the same cell with the AP photographer

00:24:31.049 --> 00:24:37.039
who wasn't released when Shariff was. That's
the power of organizing through community

00:24:37.039 --> 00:24:45.390
media. That's the power of making a demand.
When I got out they took me to, um, I was

00:24:45.390 --> 00:24:48.460
called back to the Convention Center 'cause
the media wanted to interview me about what

00:24:48.460 --> 00:24:52.230
had happened. You know more than 40 journalists
were arrested that weekend, and this is completely

00:24:52.230 --> 00:24:56.950
unacceptable. But, so, I'm brought to the
Convention Center. I'm in the NBC Skybox,

00:24:56.950 --> 00:25:00.850
and I was being interviewed. And when they
turned the camera off, there's an NBC reporter

00:25:00.850 --> 00:25:04.330
who's standing next to me. He'd been listening
to what happened, and he said, "I don't get

00:25:04.330 --> 00:25:08.110
it. Why wasn't I arrested?" I said, "Oh, were
you out covering the protest?" He said, "No."

00:25:08.110 --> 00:25:12.700
So I said, Well, I'm not being arrested in
the Skybox either." (Audience quiet laughter.)

00:25:12.700 --> 00:25:20.029
But, um, you know like Woody Allen says, 90%
of life is just showing up? So ya gotta go

00:25:20.029 --> 00:25:26.179
there. And, and it's not just because we're
curious. It's because it's our job. You know,

00:25:26.179 --> 00:25:30.700
yes, it's our job to get what's happening
on the Convention floor, the orchestrated

00:25:30.700 --> 00:25:36.010
message of the delegates. And there are differences
between them and that's interesting. Um, it's

00:25:36.010 --> 00:25:40.581
our job to get into the corporate suites,
to see who's sponsoring what. I don't know

00:25:40.581 --> 00:25:45.340
how many strawberries and hor d'oevres I reach
for and have a door slammed in my face. You

00:25:45.340 --> 00:25:49.159
know, trying to find out who's sponsoring
the Republican Governors' Association in St.

00:25:49.159 --> 00:25:54.620
Paul. Who's sponsoring the Democratic Senate
Campaign Committee in Denver, and really following

00:25:54.620 --> 00:25:59.610
the money. You know it's just a basic tenet
of good journalism. And it's our job to go

00:25:59.610 --> 00:26:04.750
into the streets. That's where the uninvited
are guests are. The thousands of people who

00:26:04.750 --> 00:26:11.730
have something else to say. Democracy is a
messy thing, and it's our job to capture it

00:26:11.730 --> 00:26:19.279
all. And we shouldn't have to get a record
to put things on the record. It's that important.

00:26:19.279 --> 00:26:24.840
Now, clearly in these cases, it's not that
dangerous, and we're also American reporters.

00:26:24.840 --> 00:26:30.230
And that makes a huge difference which brings
me to what's happening in Iraq and Afghanistan,

00:26:30.230 --> 00:26:37.240
and the incredible bravery of the reporters,
especially Iraqi reporters in Iraq. I mean,

00:26:37.240 --> 00:26:43.220
what they face, um, Arab media workers in
both Iraq and Afghanistan.

00:26:43.220 --> 00:26:48.899
Tonight I'm going to be going to the University
of California Davis, and I'll be interviewing

00:26:48.899 --> 00:26:55.951
a prison guard on stage, a prison guard from
Guantanamo. And then by video hookup we'll

00:26:55.951 --> 00:27:02.980
be speaking with Omar Deghayes who was a prisoner
at Guantanamo for many years. We'll be hooking

00:27:02.980 --> 00:27:09.760
up with him in London, in Britain. But it
makes me think of, for example, Samir Harrag.

00:27:09.760 --> 00:27:15.919
Do you know who he was? He was the Al Jazeera
reporter. He was picked up going over the

00:27:15.919 --> 00:27:23.299
border from Pakistan to Afghanistan. He was
held for more than six years at Guantanamo.

00:27:23.299 --> 00:27:29.850
Never charged. He was interrogated repeatedly,
well over a hundred times, repeatedly asked

00:27:29.850 --> 00:27:36.289
about his bosses at Al Jazeera. Can you imagine
being picked up, and you have to put yourselves

00:27:36.289 --> 00:27:43.970
in their shoes, and well, being asked about
your bosses? Um, for more than six years.

00:27:43.970 --> 00:27:51.470
And then, he's released. Then he's released.
Never charged. He's back at Al Jazeera.

00:27:51.470 --> 00:27:57.610
But actually he's lucky. What about Tariq
Ayoub? He also worked for Al Jazeera. He was

00:27:57.610 --> 00:28:03.640
the 34 year old Jordanian reporter who had
just come over the border from Jordan to work

00:28:03.640 --> 00:28:10.149
for Al Jazeera in Baghdad. This was in 2003;
this was a few weeks after the U.S. invaded.

00:28:10.149 --> 00:28:15.900
The U.S. invaded March 19th, 2003. Three weeks
later, April 8th, the day before the fall

00:28:15.900 --> 00:28:23.500
of Baghdad. Uh, Tariq has just arrived, and
he was setting the camera on the roof. You

00:28:23.500 --> 00:28:27.269
know you put the cameras on the roofs to be
able to film, but also it's very dangerous

00:28:27.269 --> 00:28:30.669
so you try to come back down very quickly
and just have the camera upstairs. Well, that

00:28:30.669 --> 00:28:35.540
morning was horrendous. It started with Abu
Dhabi TV. They were getting shelled by the

00:28:35.540 --> 00:28:40.769
United States, and the broadcasters were on
television in Baghdad and begging people to

00:28:40.769 --> 00:28:49.000
come to their aid. That was Abu Dhabi. And
then they started strafing Al Jazeera. Al

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:53.150
Jazeera had given their coordinates to the
U.S. military repeatedly. Maybe that was their

00:28:53.150 --> 00:28:59.450
problem. You know they were bombed in Afghanistan,
and then in Iraq. But this time Tariq had

00:28:59.450 --> 00:29:05.179
just gone upstairs to the roof; he'd just
set the camera, and he was immediately killed.

00:29:05.179 --> 00:29:10.310
Um, I've spoken to his wife since. Her name
is Dima Tahboub. At the funeral she said,

00:29:10.310 --> 00:29:19.070
"Hate breeds hate. The U.S. says they're fighting
terror. Who's involved in terrorism now?"

00:29:19.070 --> 00:29:26.059
And then the U.S. military set their sights
on the Palestine Hotel. You remember the Palestine

00:29:26.059 --> 00:29:32.840
Hotel where hundreds of unimbedded reporters
were. Videographers, photographers, reporters,

00:29:32.840 --> 00:29:38.640
cameramen. And there were two who were on
the balcony of their rooms. One was Taras

00:29:38.640 --> 00:29:44.960
Protsyuk. He was a Ukranian cameraman who
was reporting for Reuters. And then there

00:29:44.960 --> 00:29:53.980
was Jose Couso. Jose Couso worked for Telecinco.
I think the Spanish crew in Baghdad was the

00:29:53.980 --> 00:29:59.779
largest national crew from any country at
the Palestine Hotel. They filmed their own

00:29:59.779 --> 00:30:07.440
deaths. As U.S. military opened fire on the
Hotel, they killed both cameramen. Um, His

00:30:07.440 --> 00:30:14.500
brother, Javier, and his mother has been fighting
for years now to get justice, to bring those

00:30:14.500 --> 00:30:22.360
responsible to justice. These are the dangers
that reporters face on the ground which brings

00:30:22.360 --> 00:30:28.559
me to collateral murder in Iraq. I'm sure
that some of you here at Google have watched

00:30:28.559 --> 00:30:36.580
the videotape from Wikileaks. Uh, you know
Dan Ellsberg, an American hero, the man who

00:30:36.580 --> 00:30:42.090
worked for the Pentagon and the Rand Corporation
40 years ago, had Top Security Clearance and

00:30:42.090 --> 00:30:47.440
decided... If you ever wonder, by the way,
if protest matters, he would look outside

00:30:47.440 --> 00:30:53.370
his Pentagon window and see sometimes massive
protest, sometimes a few stragglers holding

00:30:53.370 --> 00:30:58.929
signs against the Vietnam War, and it just
started to get to him. And then heard about

00:30:58.929 --> 00:31:04.960
and met young people who were going to jail
saying they would not fight in the war. And

00:31:04.960 --> 00:31:10.549
he thought, "What am I doing to bring this
war to an end? And he realized right behind

00:31:10.549 --> 00:31:16.779
him in his safe he had the 7,000 page Top
Secret history of U.S. involvement in the

00:31:16.779 --> 00:31:21.120
war in Vietnam that only a few people had
that had been commissioned by the Secretary

00:31:21.120 --> 00:31:29.110
of War, Robert McNamara. And he decided to
open the safe and release the history. 7,000

00:31:29.110 --> 00:31:37.960
pages he Xeroxed and secreted them, and secreted
them out every single night until he had them

00:31:37.960 --> 00:31:42.980
all. And he gave them to the New York Times.
He wasn't sure the Times would ever publish

00:31:42.980 --> 00:31:49.529
them. It took many months. He was nervous;
he went underground with his wife, and he

00:31:49.529 --> 00:31:56.809
gave one stack of these 7,000 pages to Howard
Zinn, the great historian, to keep at his

00:31:56.809 --> 00:32:03.190
house. I understand Howard was here. It is
such a shame that a few months ago we lost

00:32:03.190 --> 00:32:09.039
this great humanitarian, historian who wrote
"People's History of the United States!" What

00:32:09.039 --> 00:32:18.149
a remarkable gift he gave to all of us documenting
the people's movements in this country. Um,

00:32:18.149 --> 00:32:23.580
every week I do this column, and when Howard
died...actually "Democracy Now" was broadcasting

00:32:23.580 --> 00:32:28.720
that week from, uh, from Park City, Utah.
We were at the Sundance Film Festival, and

00:32:28.720 --> 00:32:32.530
I got this call from his co-editor of "Voices
of People's History of the United States,"

00:32:32.530 --> 00:32:37.090
Anthony Arnove. That was a Thursday afternoon.
We were all set for our show on Friday, the

00:32:37.090 --> 00:32:44.710
closing broadcast from Park City, and, um,
he said, "Howard just died. He took a break;

00:32:44.710 --> 00:32:50.450
he was in California. He went swimming, and,
uh, and he had a heart attack.”

00:32:50.450 --> 00:32:54.669
Well, I mean, Howard had an amazing life.
He lived to be 87 years old.

00:32:54.669 --> 00:32:56.889
(coughing)

00:32:56.889 --> 00:33:03.539
If you haven't read his book, or you know
it, and you mean to, but you haven't actually

00:33:03.539 --> 00:33:07.889
read it, you really should. And you don't
have to take it in all at once, but the idea...

00:33:07.889 --> 00:33:14.250
Well, Howard said it very well. "The history,
not through the eyes of presidents and generals,

00:33:14.250 --> 00:33:21.000
but through the voices of ordinary people,
of rebels, of dissidents, of women, of black

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:25.580
people, of Asian Americans, of immigrants,
of socialists, and anarchists, and troublemakers

00:33:25.580 --> 00:33:32.440
of all time". I've been to a number of memorial
services for Howard Zinn now, and, um, uh,

00:33:32.440 --> 00:33:36.390
Marian Wright Edelman, who founded the Children's
Defense Fund, she was one of his students

00:33:36.390 --> 00:33:42.570
at Spelman. Alice Walker, also, as she said
he was her favorite teacher and also her funniest

00:33:42.570 --> 00:33:49.750
teacher at Spelman. Um, Marian Wright Edelman
described, uh, how daring Howard was with

00:33:49.750 --> 00:33:54.610
the students, how he would model for them.
Uh, you know they would wear, this is, uh,

00:33:54.610 --> 00:33:59.820
uh, a historically black college of women,
and in the day, they would wear white gloves

00:33:59.820 --> 00:34:06.120
and hats. And he would take them on a field
trip each year or each semester. And Marian

00:34:06.120 --> 00:34:12.180
Wright Edelman was on them to go to the Georgia
State Legislature, and to sit in the gallery

00:34:12.180 --> 00:34:17.250
to watch the Legislators. And they would sit
in the all-white section, all these African-American

00:34:17.250 --> 00:34:22.910
women with their white gloves and their hats.
And the Georgia Legislature would come to

00:34:22.910 --> 00:34:29.270
a halt. You know, this defiance, this impudence,
unacceptable. And they would then all stand

00:34:29.270 --> 00:34:38.610
up and tip their hats, smiling broadly and
walk out. Um, she said he taught her courage.

00:34:38.610 --> 00:34:44.480
Well, Howard Zinn was thrown out of Spelman
because, as Alice put it, "He loved us too

00:34:44.480 --> 00:34:49.840
much. He was thrown out because he loved us."
Alice Walker, the Pulitzer Prize Winning author

00:34:49.840 --> 00:34:55.770
now. And he was pretty excited because he
was going down to Spelman. It was 42 years

00:34:55.770 --> 00:35:01.800
after he hadn't had his contract renewed.
In other words, he was fired. 42 years later

00:35:01.800 --> 00:35:05.530
they invited him to come back and give the
commencement address, and they were giving

00:35:05.530 --> 00:35:09.950
him an honorary degree. So, if you ever think
times don't change, they do.

00:35:09.950 --> 00:35:17.890
Well, I mention Howard because, uh, Daniel
Ellsberg gave him a copy of the Pentagon Papers.

00:35:17.890 --> 00:35:24.660
But the New York Times did publish the Pentagon
Papers. And when Daniel Ellsberg speaks today,

00:35:24.660 --> 00:35:30.330
he doesn't just rest on his laurels helping
to avenge the Vietnam War by releasing these

00:35:30.330 --> 00:35:37.210
documents. In fact I introduced him at, in,
Portland, Oregon to the big event of 5,000

00:35:37.210 --> 00:35:42.730
Unitarian Universalists. And, um, I said,
"I want you to tell the story of how you actually

00:35:42.730 --> 00:35:47.110
did this." It's an amazing story, by the way.
And he said, "I don't want to talk about it.

00:35:47.110 --> 00:35:48.110
I want to talk about now."

00:35:48.110 --> 00:35:49.110
(gesturing)

00:35:49.110 --> 00:35:54.271
He, "This is 40 years ago", he said. "You
need to make sure that the Pentagon Papers

00:35:54.271 --> 00:35:59.540
are released today. Not those, but the ones
now. The ones that will end the war in Iraq

00:35:59.540 --> 00:36:05.790
and Afghanistan." I mean he is always looking
forward, and it's very important and very

00:36:05.790 --> 00:36:06.790
significant.

00:36:06.790 --> 00:36:11.670
